data.content:
## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Problem

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). Your code uses three removed APIs:

| API Found | Location | Pattern |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow for cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue execution after abort |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
                // There is NO equivalent of Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
                // If this happens, GetNextItem/ProcessItem must be fixed
                // to check the CancellationToken more frequently.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot unblock `WaitOne`/`Sleep`/IO |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — code must check the token |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids swallowing unrelated exceptions |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No rethrow to suppress; just exit the loop normally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then abort | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Join actually waits for the thread; Sleep just delays the *calling* thread blindly |

### Critical: you must also update `GetNextItem`

The biggest pitfall — if `GetNextItem()` blocks indefinitely (e.g., on a `Queue`, socket, or `WaitHandle`), cancellation will **never take effect** because cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. Fix the blocking call:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks forever until an item arrives
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // no way to interrupt this
}

// AFTER: unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken) throws
    // OperationCanceledException when the token fires
    return _queue.Take(token);
}
```

If you're using a `ManualResetEvent` or similar:
```csharp
// Replace event.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

### Common pitfalls for this migration

1. **Not passing the token to blocking calls** — The #1 mistake. If `GetNextItem` blocks without checking the token, `Stop()` hangs forever. There is no force-kill equivalent in modern .NET.

2. **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — It holds timer/callback resources. Always `Dispose()` it.

3. **Losing the rollback logic** — The old `catch (ThreadAbortException)` block contained `RollbackCurrentTransaction()`. Make sure this moves to the `catch (OperationCanceledException)` block, not just deleted.

4. **Assuming cancellation is instant** — It only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` runs for 30 seconds with no token check, cancellation waits 30 seconds. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long operations.

5. **The "uncooperative code" escape hatch** — If you truly cannot modify `GetNextItem` (e.g., third-party library with no cancellation support), the only option is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort`.
